MARBURG HEMORRHAGIC FEVER - ANGOLA (11): AGE DISTRIBUTION
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 31 Mar 2005
From: Daniel G. Bausch <dbausch@tulane.edu>

The 1998/2000 Outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo
---------------------------------------------------
By coincidence, we are just about to submit a manuscript detailing the
1998-2000 outbreak of Marburg hemorrhagic fever (MHF) in Durba, Democratic
Republic of the Congo (DRC). In light of the current events in Angola,
some of these data may be of interest here. A total of 154 cases were
identified, with a case fatality of 83 percent. The mean age was 28 years
(range: 7 days to 72 years). Only 12 (8 percent) of the cases were under
age 5, and the case fatality for this group was the same. Most cases were
in young males exposed in nearby gold mines. Secondary transmission in the
household appeared to be limited. There was evidence of transmission of
Marburg virus in the region prior to 1998, but that did not result in a
high prevalence of antibody in the population (1).
Although precise calculations are close to impossible, age-stratified
attack rates appear to vary significantly between filovirus outbreaks. The
relatively low incidence of pediatric cases of Ebola-Zaire during the 1995
outbreak in Kikwit, DRC, prompted theories of natural immunity in children.
These theories were scrapped after the 2000 Ebola-Sudan outbreak in Gulu,
Uganda, where fatal infection in children was common.
MHF fever is too rare to have enough data on potential links between a
particular genotype and virulence, especially any age-stratified data.
Previous infection and immunity could result in what is being seen in
Angola, and ProMED-mail has listed previous outbreaks of hemorrhagic
illness in Angola that could have been MHF. However, I have my doubts that
transmission would have been so widespread (and non-fatal) to result in
appreciable population immunity of older age groups.
I suspect that the age distribution of cases in Angola will ultimately turn
out to have more of a behavioral basis, as opposed to biological. The most
common point source when a cluster of VHF is seen is the hospital. It is
not clear from the ProMED-mail listings how many of the children might have
been seen and potentially exposed at the same health facility. An outbreak
of Lassa fever in Sierra Leone in 2004 in which pediatric cases
predominated was ultimately thought to be linked to contaminated multi-dose
vials (2). If the hospital can reasonably be excluded, less obvious sources
need to be considered. Do children enter for play or work (even very young
children often help with family chores in sub-Saharan Africa) into caves
where bats, a leading reservoir candidate, roost? Do children find and eat
fruit that could be contaminated by bat guano? Sequence data, no doubt
forthcoming, should shed light on whether this appears to more of a point
source outbreak or multiple introductions, facilitating the generation of
hypotheses to be investigated.
References:
1. Bausch DG et al. Risk factors for Marburg hemorrhagic fever, Democratic
Republic of the Congo. Emerg Infect Dis. 2003 Dec;9(12):1531-7.
2. Update on Lassa fever in West Africa, WHO Weekly Epidemiological Record,
11 March 2005, No. 10, 2005, 80, 85-92.
--
Daniel G. Bausch, MD, MPH&TM
Associate Professor
Department of Tropical Medicine, SL-17
J. Bennet Johnston Building, Rm. 511
