Date: Wed 31 Mar 2005
From: Mike Thomas <michael.thomas@gd-ais.com>

Angola: A Comment on Marburg Virus Transmission
-----------------------------------------------
There has been speculation about the role of bats as a possible reservoir
for Ebola and Marburg viruses (1). I understand that Marburg virus has
some phylogenetic similarity to _Paramyxoviridae_.
There was a previous ProMED-mail report about Nipah virus ( a member of
_Paramyxoviridae_) transmission to humans attributed to eating fruit
contaminated by bat excreta (2). Another such report suggested that
certain fruit drops from trees at night after being partially eaten by a
bat, and then children collect and eat the unwashed contaminated fruit.
This was suggested as an explanation for fatal cases of Nipah virus
infection in one outbreak occurring in persons not more than 15 years of age.
Since the reported cases of Marburg hemorrhagic fever in Angola are
predominantly in children, I wonder if there is a fruit that tends to be
given to local children in this age group and if this fruit is
contaminated? This age group is also more likely to place objects in the
mouth that are contaminated with excreta from peridomestic rodents. This
could provide an alternate explanation of oral ingestion of virus. Parts of
northern Angola experienced flooding this year, which might suggest a
season of heavy rains and subsequent irruptions in the bat or small mammal
population (4). I understand that at least part of Uige province in Angola
is forested.
References
----------
(1) Peterson AT, Carroll DS, Mills JN, Johnson KM. Potential Mammalian
Filovirus Reservoirs. Energizing Infectious Diseases 10(12):2073-2081.
(2) ProMEd-mail. 25 JAN 2005 (20050125.0267).
(3) ProMED-mail. 22 NOV 2004 (20041122.3124).
(4) Schuur EAG. Productivity and Global Climate Revisited: The Sensitivity
of Tropical Forest Growth to Precipitiation.
--
Mike Thomas, DO, MPH&TM
Chief Scientist
General Dynamics - AIS
Arlington, Virginia USA
<michael.thomas@gd-ais.com>
[Professor Bausch's analysis of data from the 1998-2000 outbreak of Marburg
hemorrhagic fever in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) will provide an
interesting background for comparison with the situation in the current
outbreak in Angola, particularly with regard to the limited extent of
secondary transmission and low prevalence of specific antibody observed in
the DRC. We appreciate Dr Bausch's cooperation in making these data
available for posting on ProMED-mail.
Both Mike Thomas and Daniel Bausch have raised the question of the role of
bats as potential reservoirs and vectors of Marburg hemorrhagic fever virus
and suggest that exposure to virus-contaminated fruit might explain
the apparent greater vulnerability of young children to infection. This is
an intriguing suggestion, and it would be interesting to know the relative
abidance of frugivorous bats in the region. It is tempting to make the
comparison with transmission of Nipah virus in East Asia; however, it
should be stressed that the phylogenetic link between the _Filoviridae_ and
the _Paramyxovviridae_ is weak and does not imply any similarity in
biological properties. - Mod.CP]
